WEBVTT

00:02.911 --> 00:06.548
[GIRLS HUMMING]

00:18.092 --> 00:21.696
[SUSPENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

01:01.735 --> 01:03.904
[GIRLS HUMMING]

01:05.372 --> 01:07.809
[DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING]

02:30.107 --> 02:35.107
Subtitles by explosiveskull

02:37.165 --> 02:38.265
MAN: <i>This morning,</i>

02:38.499 --> 02:40.968
<i>the British Ambassador
in Berlin...</i>

02:41.501 --> 02:45.171
<i>handed the German government
a final note...</i>

02:46.005 --> 02:51.011
<i>stating that unless we heard
from them by 11 o'clock...</i>

02:52.045 --> 02:54.246
<i>that they were prepared at once,</i>

02:54.248 --> 02:56.951
<i>to withdraw their troops
from Poland.</i>

02:57.350 --> 03:00.654
<i>A state of war would exist
between us.</i>

03:02.623 --> 03:04.257
<i>I have to tell you now...</i>

03:04.825 --> 03:07.929
<i>that no such undertaking
has been received...</i>

03:08.896 --> 03:10.263
<i>and that consequently,</i>

03:10.598 --> 03:14.635
<i>this country is at war
with Germany.</i>

03:23.310 --> 03:25.112
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

03:28.582 --> 03:30.518
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

03:44.164 --> 03:45.465
Joseph Von Hammersmark?

03:45.832 --> 03:47.801
- Yes.
- I am Officer Dietrich.

03:48.035 --> 03:50.568
I have been sent
by the Reich commissioner,

03:50.570 --> 03:51.838
Heinrich Himmler.

03:52.206 --> 03:54.409
Yes, of course. Please, come in.

04:04.417 --> 04:05.819
JOSEPH: This is my wife,

04:06.487 --> 04:08.423
- Eva.
- Well...

04:09.255 --> 04:10.289
a pleasure.

04:10.791 --> 04:12.894
We are honored to welcome you
to our home.

04:14.394 --> 04:16.362
You appear to have met with,

04:16.661 --> 04:18.499
a little accident, no?

04:21.569 --> 04:23.270
Y... yeah. Um,

04:23.569 --> 04:25.105
I fell down the stairs.

04:28.574 --> 04:29.976
JOSEPH: Would you like a drink?

04:30.309 --> 04:31.946
Eva can bring it to us.

04:33.013 --> 04:34.047
DIETRICH: No.

04:34.780 --> 04:37.617
Thank you.
I have other appointments today.

04:38.050 --> 04:41.555
- Let us proceed.
- Of course. Please, follow me.

04:50.064 --> 04:52.700
Ah, the reason we are here.

05:02.175 --> 05:06.948
So, Herr Von Hammersmark,
how did you come to write

05:07.215 --> 05:08.549
such a book?

05:08.949 --> 05:10.316
[CLOCK TICKING]

05:10.550 --> 05:12.119
In this book I compiled,

05:12.619 --> 05:14.821
mystical recitations and spells,

05:15.122 --> 05:19.225
using the various practices
I observed in Tibet and Egypt.

05:19.660 --> 05:21.963
What price do you want...

05:22.728 --> 05:26.800
<i>for your unique and marvelous...</i>

05:27.533 --> 05:29.135
<i>creation?</i>

05:33.907 --> 05:35.877
I will write it down for you.

05:36.910 --> 05:37.979
As you wish.

05:48.021 --> 05:49.991
[SIGHS]

05:52.492 --> 05:53.827
Ah!

05:54.660 --> 05:58.298
So... you know the real worth
of it.

06:00.133 --> 06:01.536
That may be so...

06:02.169 --> 06:03.170
but in Bavaria,

06:03.470 --> 06:04.972
we have an old saying.

06:06.006 --> 06:07.074
When the farmer,

06:07.441 --> 06:09.042
wants a cow,

06:09.275 --> 06:11.812
first he must taste the milk.

06:48.581 --> 06:52.319
[SPEAKING ITALIAN]

07:24.251 --> 07:25.720
[DIETRICH APPLAUDS] Wonderful.

07:26.453 --> 07:28.589
Very good, Herr Hammersmark.

07:29.189 --> 07:31.423
I shall inform
the Reich commissioner

07:31.425 --> 07:33.828
of the book's authenticity.

07:34.694 --> 07:36.462
And we shall release,

07:36.730 --> 07:40.400
half of the funds
immediately into your account.

07:40.634 --> 07:42.535
<i>Within 48 hours
it will have cleared.</i>

07:42.937 --> 07:45.573
<i>I will return here then,
pick up the book,</i>

07:45.840 --> 07:48.342
and then the rest
of the money shall be paid.

07:49.809 --> 07:52.278
Do we have an understanding?

07:54.848 --> 07:56.149
Yes.

07:56.650 --> 07:58.185
Good.

08:13.199 --> 08:14.333
Good afternoon,

08:14.634 --> 08:16.336
Frau Von Hammersmark.

08:17.103 --> 08:18.171
Afternoon.

08:25.612 --> 08:26.779
[DOOR CLOSING]

08:27.079 --> 08:30.183
JOSEPH: So you like listening
to other people's conversations.

08:30.751 --> 08:32.216
- I wasn't.
- Don't lie to me.

08:32.217 --> 08:33.951
[EVA GASPING]

08:33.953 --> 08:36.687
Maybe this professor needs
to teach you a lesson.

08:36.688 --> 08:38.990
No. No more, Joseph.
Please. No...

08:38.991 --> 08:42.195
Now when you've waited a moment
for the lesson to sink in...

08:45.933 --> 08:47.333
bring me a sandwich.

08:52.405 --> 08:53.708
[DOOR CREAKING]

09:00.146 --> 09:01.214
[OWL HOOTING]

10:30.270 --> 10:31.539
[CLANKING]

12:05.464 --> 12:08.035
[CAR APPROACHING]

12:31.824 --> 12:33.026
Thanks for stopping.

12:34.160 --> 12:35.628
Has your car broken down?

12:36.663 --> 12:38.299
Unfortunately, yes.

12:39.532 --> 12:40.633
I'm Frederick.

12:41.400 --> 12:42.402
Frederick Voller.

12:43.170 --> 12:44.237
I'm Eva.

12:44.771 --> 12:46.040
Do you need a lift?

12:47.339 --> 12:49.275
Will you be passing Kulmbach?

12:49.910 --> 12:51.377
Oh, um...

12:51.911 --> 12:53.513
well, that is quite a distance.

12:53.981 --> 12:55.181
It's okay.

12:55.781 --> 12:57.483
I understand if it's too far.

12:59.285 --> 13:01.755
No, it... it actually suits me.

13:02.454 --> 13:04.590
I'm trying to get as far away
as I can.

13:07.394 --> 13:08.395
Thank you.

13:14.767 --> 13:18.104
[ENGINE STARTING]

13:25.045 --> 13:27.314
I wouldn't normally stop
for a stranger...

13:28.548 --> 13:30.117
but I'm so tired.

13:30.883 --> 13:33.119
Perhaps the company
will keep me awake.

13:33.819 --> 13:35.487
Have you been driving
for a while?

13:35.722 --> 13:37.091
Couple of hours.

13:38.091 --> 13:40.327
I've come
from the Volcet-Teigen district.

13:53.207 --> 13:56.042
You said you were just trying
to get as far away as you can.

13:56.508 --> 13:58.511
You have no particular place
in mind?

13:59.612 --> 14:01.611
To be honest,
I wasn't thinking very clearly

14:01.613 --> 14:02.648
when I left.

14:03.315 --> 14:05.585
Something to do with the bruises
on your face?

14:13.327 --> 14:17.131
Sorry. Overstepped the mark.
None of my business.

14:18.765 --> 14:20.232
It's always been my problem.

14:21.067 --> 14:23.670
Sometimes I speak
before I think. Sorry.

14:26.006 --> 14:27.374
It's fine.

14:28.007 --> 14:29.775
My husband is not a good man.

14:30.242 --> 14:31.778
Let's just leave it at that.

14:32.545 --> 14:33.747
So we leave it.

14:36.115 --> 14:38.085
We all make mistakes in life.

14:38.919 --> 14:40.386
I know what you mean.

14:42.588 --> 14:44.090
I made a few myself.

16:01.601 --> 16:03.433
What the fuck you think
you're doing?

16:03.435 --> 16:04.203
I, uh...

16:04.304 --> 16:05.804
Put your hands
on the steering wheel...

16:06.405 --> 16:09.476
or I put a bullet
in that pretty face of yours.

16:14.514 --> 16:16.250
What were you reaching for?

16:17.717 --> 16:18.785
The cash?

16:19.752 --> 16:21.487
- No.
- Oh...

16:22.256 --> 16:23.756
the gun then.

16:24.190 --> 16:26.692
I just wanted to protect myself.

16:26.892 --> 16:28.259
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

16:28.261 --> 16:29.762
You have nothing to fear...

16:30.697 --> 16:32.866
as long as you do exactly
as I tell you.

16:35.202 --> 16:36.737
What do you want me to do?

16:38.371 --> 16:39.905
I need to get to Kulmbach.

16:40.439 --> 16:42.242
You're going to drive me there.

16:42.843 --> 16:43.910
You stay calm...

16:44.544 --> 16:46.246
and I won't give you
any trouble.

16:48.481 --> 16:50.484
If you try to fuck with me...

16:51.517 --> 16:54.253
I have six little friends
who will fuck with you.

16:54.688 --> 16:58.389
- Understand?
- Wh... wh... why do you need me?

16:58.391 --> 17:00.961
Why can't you just take the car?
Take the car.

17:02.127 --> 17:03.162
I could.

17:03.697 --> 17:05.797
If I find myself
in a tight situation,

17:05.799 --> 17:06.900
you know, I...

17:07.768 --> 17:09.469
a hostage could be useful.

17:11.904 --> 17:13.240
You have a problem with that?

17:14.973 --> 17:16.242
No.

17:16.842 --> 17:17.877
Good.

17:20.012 --> 17:21.348
Then, let's go.

17:28.421 --> 17:31.758
[ENGINE STARTING]

17:38.598 --> 17:40.767
That fucking bitch has the book.

17:41.401 --> 17:43.970
DIETRICH: <i>Okay, calm down,
Herr Von Hammersmark.</i>

17:44.236 --> 17:45.838
<i>The deal is still on.</i>

17:46.473 --> 17:48.040
I've got to find her!

17:48.741 --> 17:51.144
DIETRICH: <i>Just stay home
and keep calm.</i>

17:51.444 --> 17:52.980
<i>We will take care of it.</i>

18:08.994 --> 18:10.162
What do you want me to do?

18:10.563 --> 18:12.732
Keep your mouth shut
and do as I tell you.

18:13.666 --> 18:15.467
As far they're concerned,
we're a married couple

18:15.469 --> 18:18.038
on the way to visit
my sister Edith in Kulmbach.

18:18.871 --> 18:21.841
How long have we been married,
in case they ask?

18:22.742 --> 18:23.776
Ten years.

18:24.344 --> 18:26.680
Be careful of the miserable
look on your face.

18:28.348 --> 18:29.614
FREDERICK: Just because
I'm putting this away,

18:29.616 --> 18:31.217
don't think
you can try anything.

18:31.885 --> 18:33.584
It only takes a second
to take it out

18:33.586 --> 18:36.988
and repaint the inside
of this car with your brains.

18:36.990 --> 18:38.392
[SQUEAKING]

18:39.960 --> 18:41.094
State your business.

18:41.661 --> 18:45.532
We are visiting
my husband's sister in Kulmbach.

18:45.964 --> 18:47.932
- Name?
- Frederick Voller.

18:47.934 --> 18:49.235
This is my wife Eva.

18:49.703 --> 18:52.069
How long do you expect
to stay in Kulmbach?

18:52.071 --> 18:53.506
Um, three days.

18:59.311 --> 19:00.613
OFFICER: Okay.

19:03.415 --> 19:05.085
I'm going to speak
to my colleague...

19:06.052 --> 19:07.420
over there...

19:08.287 --> 19:09.523
and then...

19:10.290 --> 19:11.825
we'll wave you through.

19:13.193 --> 19:14.761
Thank you, officer.

19:19.165 --> 19:20.466
What is the problem?

19:21.800 --> 19:23.803
She's giving me
some suspicious look.

19:24.337 --> 19:25.536
Some weird eyes.

19:25.538 --> 19:27.574
They said they were going
to Kulmbach but...

19:31.377 --> 19:33.713
You think you are so clever,
don't you?

19:38.483 --> 19:41.754
Simply tell them what to do
and go from there.

20:08.748 --> 20:09.783
So,

20:10.082 --> 20:12.551
look at the traffic policeman.

20:13.153 --> 20:14.887
How's that going for you, huh?

20:24.431 --> 20:26.767
[GASPING]

21:12.511 --> 21:14.447
[VINES CRACKS]

21:54.886 --> 21:57.022
You have a lot of fight in you.

21:58.390 --> 21:59.892
Are you going to kill me?

22:02.462 --> 22:03.696
No.

22:05.298 --> 22:06.599
Not yet.

22:06.999 --> 22:08.000
Why not?

22:08.501 --> 22:10.936
You remind me of a dog
that I used to have.

22:12.538 --> 22:14.808
She used to piss
all over the carpet...

22:15.774 --> 22:17.276
but I still kept her.

22:19.011 --> 22:20.579
I don't need your pity.

22:22.181 --> 22:23.583
Would you rather I kill you now?

22:23.982 --> 22:26.819
Is that what you want?
Die here in these woods

22:27.119 --> 22:29.588
as the fucking birds
peck out your eyeballs?

22:30.123 --> 22:32.789
Then, a dog walker passes by
in a couple of weeks

22:32.791 --> 22:35.194
and discovers your
maggot-ridden remains?

22:35.426 --> 22:37.530
What other option do I have?

22:45.972 --> 22:49.608
- Come with me to Kulmbach.
- [EVA BREATHING HEAVILY]

22:57.950 --> 22:59.920
You're enjoying this,
aren't you?

23:01.620 --> 23:02.922
Enjoying?

23:04.557 --> 23:06.092
- No.
- [GASPS]

23:06.692 --> 23:10.029
Simply making the best
out of a bad situation.

23:10.229 --> 23:11.831
[YELLS]

23:12.530 --> 23:13.966
I suggest...

23:14.701 --> 23:16.036
you do the same.

23:31.584 --> 23:34.588
- [TIRE BURSTS]
- [TIRES SQUEALING]

23:35.488 --> 23:37.090
FREDERICK:
What the fuck happened?

23:43.761 --> 23:45.762
The tire on this side has burst.

23:45.764 --> 23:47.633
The one on this side
is down, too.

23:50.368 --> 23:51.737
Couldn't have been a blowout.

23:52.004 --> 23:53.872
Not two tires at the same time.

23:55.975 --> 23:58.142
Must have been some glass
in the road back there.

23:58.144 --> 23:59.444
Fuck sake!

23:59.979 --> 24:01.982
We will walk to that house
over there.

24:03.081 --> 24:05.385
Same shit as before.
We're a married couple, okay?

24:05.717 --> 24:08.050
We tell whoever lives there
our car has broken down.

24:08.052 --> 24:11.223
We need to phone a friend of
mine to come out and pick us up.

24:12.124 --> 24:13.159
Come.

24:14.293 --> 24:16.061
Don't try anything stupid.

24:16.930 --> 24:18.231
When my friend gets here,

24:18.830 --> 24:20.199
I will let you go.

24:21.233 --> 24:22.234
Will you?

24:24.671 --> 24:25.938
I promise.

24:26.472 --> 24:28.340
[SCOFFS] How can I trust you?

24:28.875 --> 24:30.844
You're still alive, aren't you?

24:42.620 --> 24:44.189
Ah, good evening.

24:45.057 --> 24:47.657
My, I'm sorry to disturb
you at this late hour,

24:47.659 --> 24:49.794
but our car has broken down.

24:50.396 --> 24:53.132
I hate to impose, but do you
have a phone we could use?

24:53.866 --> 24:56.368
- Of course. Come in.
- Thank you.

25:02.242 --> 25:04.376
[DOOR CREAKS]

25:06.078 --> 25:08.147
[DOOR CLOSES]

25:12.585 --> 25:14.285
- My name's Helmut.
- Frederick.

25:14.287 --> 25:15.989
Uh, this is my wife Eva.

25:16.856 --> 25:18.557
A pleasure to meet you both.

25:18.890 --> 25:21.357
I'm just preparing dinner.
It's nothing much,

25:21.359 --> 25:23.396
but you're welcome to join me
if you like.

25:23.695 --> 25:24.930
The phone is in the kitchen.

25:25.298 --> 25:27.300
You can kill two birds
with one stone

25:27.634 --> 25:30.136
- so to speak.
- That would be lovely.

25:31.869 --> 25:33.606
Wouldn't that be lovely, dear?

25:34.072 --> 25:36.309
Yeah. That would be lovely.

25:52.925 --> 25:56.061
- EVA: We are going to Kulmbach.
- HELMUT: Visiting friends?

25:56.796 --> 26:00.066
Family.
My husband's sister lives there.

26:03.301 --> 26:05.370
HELMUT: Did you fall over
on the way here?

26:05.570 --> 26:06.672
What?

26:07.005 --> 26:08.774
The bruises on your face.

26:10.475 --> 26:11.578
No, um...

26:12.278 --> 26:14.613
the... the tire
on the car blew, I...

26:15.114 --> 26:17.383
I jerked forward
and hit the steering wheel.

26:19.217 --> 26:21.186
They look more
like knuckle marks.

26:21.753 --> 26:23.122
[MUSIC PLAYING ON THE RADIO]

26:25.758 --> 26:27.726
Thank you, Helmut.
This is wonderful.

26:28.059 --> 26:29.127
HELMUT: How was your phone call?

26:29.461 --> 26:32.628
Ah, good. I have a friend
who lives an hour's drive away.

26:32.630 --> 26:34.434
He's on his way to pick us up.

26:36.034 --> 26:38.368
Well, you're both welcome
to wait here until then.

26:38.370 --> 26:40.139
Ah, thank you. Very kind.

26:40.839 --> 26:42.138
Not at all.

26:42.140 --> 26:44.944
I was just telling your wife
I'm glad of the company.

26:45.377 --> 26:48.147
- It gets lonely here.
- FREDERICK: Not married then?

26:48.647 --> 26:49.948
No.

26:50.950 --> 26:52.218
FREDERICK: Probably
for the best.

26:53.751 --> 26:55.421
Women are not the
easiest creatures.

27:00.358 --> 27:01.860
Can I use your bathroom?

27:02.494 --> 27:04.629
Of course. Down the hallway.

27:04.963 --> 27:06.465
Second door on your right.

27:06.898 --> 27:08.367
FREDERICK: Hurry back,
sweetheart.

27:09.768 --> 27:11.571
Don't want your meal to spoil.

27:12.672 --> 27:15.040
[MUSIC PLAYING ON RADIO]

27:16.742 --> 27:18.410
What do you need that for?

27:20.512 --> 27:22.214
I have things I need to use.

27:23.616 --> 27:25.017
FREDERICK: Fine.

27:25.350 --> 27:26.485
Don't be long.

27:29.489 --> 27:30.590
So,

27:31.057 --> 27:32.692
how long have you two
been married?

27:32.992 --> 27:35.360
Hm. Ten years.

27:37.229 --> 27:39.198
I guess it's true what they say.

27:39.565 --> 27:40.834
What do they say?

27:41.500 --> 27:43.269
Familiarity breeds contempt.

27:56.549 --> 27:59.617
You do not think I treat
my wife well, Helmut?

28:00.219 --> 28:01.987
Don't pay any attention to me.

28:02.421 --> 28:04.723
I don't get to see many people
these days.

28:05.257 --> 28:08.228
Perhaps my social graces
aren't what they used to be.

28:11.730 --> 28:12.999
Clearly not.

28:16.469 --> 28:17.503
So...

28:19.738 --> 28:21.441
never been married, Helmut?

28:24.242 --> 28:25.444
No.

28:25.810 --> 28:27.045
FREDERICK: Hm.

28:28.079 --> 28:29.616
Guess it is true what they say.

28:30.982 --> 28:32.484
And what do they say?

28:34.752 --> 28:36.521
There's no romance without...

28:37.423 --> 28:38.524
finance.

28:45.063 --> 28:48.367
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

28:52.137 --> 28:55.407
So Eva, married for ten years,
hm?

28:56.341 --> 28:57.376
That's right.

28:57.909 --> 28:59.344
I find that curious.

29:00.146 --> 29:01.213
Do you?

29:01.446 --> 29:02.514
HELMUT: Very.

29:03.514 --> 29:06.351
And why do you find
that curious, Helmut?

29:06.652 --> 29:08.354
I find it a little curious...

29:09.021 --> 29:11.389
why a man who has been married
for ten years...

29:11.956 --> 29:13.857
would question his wife
taking her handbag

29:13.859 --> 29:15.328
to the bathroom.

29:19.063 --> 29:20.665
And why is that curious?

29:21.032 --> 29:23.635
Well, I may not be married,

29:23.935 --> 29:26.239
but I've been around
many women in my life.

29:27.173 --> 29:29.241
A woman takes her handbag
everywhere.

29:29.774 --> 29:31.576
Particularly to the bathroom.

29:35.181 --> 29:37.016
If you have a problem...

29:38.384 --> 29:40.953
perhaps you had better
just come out with it.

29:42.221 --> 29:43.256
Well...

29:44.822 --> 29:46.524
maybe you two aren't married.

29:47.092 --> 29:48.627
[FREDERICK LAUGHS
AND THUMPS]

29:50.663 --> 29:51.896
Let me get this straight.

29:52.097 --> 29:56.801
You think because Eva
and I are a little rusty

29:57.101 --> 29:58.704
that we are not married?

30:01.005 --> 30:02.839
No offense,
but you clearly do not know

30:02.841 --> 30:04.309
much about being married.

30:04.876 --> 30:06.445
That's not the only thing.

30:11.482 --> 30:12.551
Well...

30:13.551 --> 30:15.118
what else?

30:15.120 --> 30:17.223
You aren't wearing
a wedding ring.

30:18.857 --> 30:20.225
She is...

30:21.493 --> 30:22.595
but you aren't.

30:24.396 --> 30:27.232
Not that this
is any of your business but...

30:28.701 --> 30:30.403
I lost my ring.

30:31.037 --> 30:32.638
Perhaps that's the case...

30:34.540 --> 30:36.209
and perhaps it's not.

30:48.654 --> 30:51.656
I have had just about as much
as I can take of you,

30:52.023 --> 30:53.392
pig fucker!

30:54.059 --> 30:55.461
[GUN COCKS]

30:56.194 --> 30:57.896
Where the fuck did you get that?

30:58.196 --> 31:00.698
Helmut has quite the collection
in the living room.

31:00.932 --> 31:02.602
Guess you missed that, huh?

31:05.203 --> 31:07.773
You want this cattle molester
to bite the bullet?

31:08.140 --> 31:11.209
Do you want your balls to end up
on his kitchen floor?

31:13.345 --> 31:17.083
- Put the gun down.
- Put your fucking gun down!

31:20.118 --> 31:22.386
You have a lot of rage
inside you.

31:22.953 --> 31:24.790
Caused by assholes like you.

31:25.057 --> 31:26.357
No more.

31:27.459 --> 31:31.597
The most terrifying people
in this world are not too bad.

31:31.829 --> 31:34.833
Show their rage and commits
the crimes of passion.

31:35.934 --> 31:37.235
No.

31:39.104 --> 31:40.639
The most terrifying...

31:41.373 --> 31:44.677
are the ones who can kill
another human being...

31:45.644 --> 31:47.346
without hesitation...

31:49.214 --> 31:50.683
without emotion.

31:52.451 --> 31:54.587
They go
about their daily life...

31:55.221 --> 31:57.155
with no remorse.

32:01.194 --> 32:03.128
You are not one
of those people...

32:05.630 --> 32:06.698
but I am.

32:07.232 --> 32:09.167
You think you are invincible.

32:09.801 --> 32:10.935
You are not.

32:11.569 --> 32:16.541
Now, last chance.
Put the fucking gun down!

32:27.152 --> 32:28.554
[GUN CLANKS]

32:29.954 --> 32:31.189
So...

32:31.924 --> 32:33.259
now what?

32:34.626 --> 32:38.297
You get down on your knees and...
and beg for your life.

32:39.298 --> 32:40.766
I've already told you.

32:41.200 --> 32:42.468
You're not a killer.

32:43.534 --> 32:45.470
EVA: We will soon see, won't we?

32:48.507 --> 32:50.342
Before you pull the trigger,

32:50.876 --> 32:52.008
would you like a little insight

32:52.010 --> 32:54.780
into what it feels like
to kill someone?

32:55.813 --> 32:57.482
I will know soon enough.

32:58.983 --> 33:01.853
You know, the first time
is the hardest.

33:02.954 --> 33:03.990
It's like,

33:04.423 --> 33:06.592
a piece of you dies...

33:07.192 --> 33:08.761
along with your victim.

33:11.963 --> 33:13.329
I remember
feeling quite different

33:13.331 --> 33:14.699
after my first kill.

33:15.267 --> 33:16.736
I never figured out why...

33:18.303 --> 33:19.738
but now I know.

33:22.340 --> 33:24.842
My humanity died right there
and then.

33:25.243 --> 33:27.545
Do you think it will
be different for you?

33:27.745 --> 33:28.880
You are wrong.

33:30.115 --> 33:32.251
But if you take
another human life...

33:32.851 --> 33:35.487
you will never find peace again.

33:36.154 --> 33:37.790
S... stop talking!

33:40.693 --> 33:41.961
Fucking bitch!

33:52.905 --> 33:54.706
He wasn't your husband,
was he?

33:56.741 --> 33:59.779
He... he was a criminal
who kept me hostage.

34:01.012 --> 34:02.781
You don't have to worry
about this.

34:03.515 --> 34:05.383
But I am part of a murder.

34:05.951 --> 34:07.152
I'll take care of it.

34:07.551 --> 34:09.286
I'll bury him in the garden.

34:10.188 --> 34:12.257
No one needs to find out
about this.

34:14.891 --> 34:16.393
Why are you helping me?

34:17.963 --> 34:19.197
What you said before...

34:19.998 --> 34:23.034
about being treated like shit
by arseholes like him.

34:24.034 --> 34:26.705
It seems like you've lost
your faith in humanity.

34:27.705 --> 34:29.371
Perhaps the kindness
of a stranger

34:29.373 --> 34:31.342
can help restore that faith.

34:35.179 --> 34:36.482
Thank you.

34:38.248 --> 34:42.786
[RAIN PATTERING]

35:01.106 --> 35:02.340
It's all right.

35:03.107 --> 35:04.376
No.

35:04.709 --> 35:05.810
I want to.

35:31.836 --> 35:33.805
[DOOR CLOSES]

36:22.321 --> 36:23.823
COLONEL VON: Dietrich...

36:25.256 --> 36:26.825
it's Colonel Von Braun.

36:27.859 --> 36:29.227
I have the book.

36:29.894 --> 36:32.530
Pay a visit
to Joseph Von Hammersmark.

36:33.131 --> 36:35.100
Inform him of developments.

36:41.039 --> 36:43.475
- DIETRICH: Herr Von Hammersmark?
- JOSEPH: Yes. Please, come in.

36:45.910 --> 36:47.944
- Have you found my wife?
- Yes, we have.

36:47.946 --> 36:50.546
- Did she have the book?
- Yes, she had the book.

36:50.548 --> 36:52.314
Oh, thank god.
So the deal is still on?

36:52.316 --> 36:53.649
Oh, of course
the deal is still on.

36:53.651 --> 36:56.588
In fact, they have sent me here
to finalize

36:56.921 --> 36:58.889
- the agreement.
- JOSEPH: Great. Where is it?

36:59.223 --> 37:00.492
Oh, I have it here.

37:00.624 --> 37:03.459
But first of all, are you not
going to offer me a drink?

37:03.461 --> 37:05.497
- I have come a long way.
- JOSEPH: I'm sorry.

37:05.731 --> 37:07.663
I didn't mean to be rude.
It's been a worrying day.

37:07.665 --> 37:09.232
My mind's been all
over the place.

37:09.234 --> 37:10.402
You understand, I'm sure.

37:10.734 --> 37:12.470
Indeed it is understandable.

37:12.838 --> 37:14.106
What would you like to drink?

37:14.205 --> 37:18.174
Ah, a cup of tea, please,
for us civilized gentlemen.

37:18.176 --> 37:20.142
No problem.
Please, come through.

37:20.144 --> 37:21.546
[GUN COCKS]

38:05.423 --> 38:07.560
[WOODS CRACKLING]

38:35.586 --> 38:37.222
One of our historians,

38:37.589 --> 38:39.991
Benjamin Hoffman,
stole the book.

38:40.557 --> 38:42.459
<i>He fled to the town
of Rosenheim...</i>

38:42.961 --> 38:45.363
<i>and took up shelter
in the home of a family.</i>

38:46.064 --> 38:48.966
<i>Kristoff Muller,
his wife Bridgette,</i>

38:49.301 --> 38:50.903
<i>and their daughter Esther.</i>

38:51.970 --> 38:54.337
Colonel Von Avenslaven
and his men took care

38:54.339 --> 38:56.675
- of the parents.
- BRIDGETTE: No!

38:59.977 --> 39:02.046
COLONEL VON: <i>But the daughter
fled with the book.</i>

39:03.448 --> 39:05.584
We have no idea
what happened to her.

39:06.685 --> 39:08.651
All we know is the book
ended up in the hands

39:08.653 --> 39:10.022
of a local toy maker.

39:10.990 --> 39:12.857
Amos Blackfoot.

39:13.524 --> 39:15.793
<i>According to the
information we received,</i>

39:16.361 --> 39:19.298
Blackfoot used the book
to bring his dolls to life.

39:30.742 --> 39:33.278
He was caught
by Von Avenslaven's men.

39:35.481 --> 39:37.549
As unlikely as it sounds.

39:38.182 --> 39:40.350
It is believed the dolls
killed the Colonel

39:40.352 --> 39:44.890
and three SS officers
at the base in upper Bavaria.

39:48.260 --> 39:50.595
[YELLING]

39:51.229 --> 39:52.298
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

39:56.001 --> 39:58.703
The toymaker escaped
with the book.

40:02.274 --> 40:03.675
This is the toymaker.

40:04.109 --> 40:06.377
The target
of your undercover mission.

40:06.877 --> 40:08.379
You are to infiltrate a train

40:08.847 --> 40:11.515
<i>traveling from the town
of Rosenheim to Nuremberg.</i>

40:12.149 --> 40:15.452
<i>Our intelligence tells us
the Toymaker will be onboard.</i>

40:15.819 --> 40:17.222
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING]

40:17.488 --> 40:19.824
COLONEL VON: <i>We suspect he will
attempt to change trains at Nuremberg</i>

40:20.091 --> 40:22.060
<i>and head to either
Amsterdam or Prague.</i>

40:23.394 --> 40:27.698
You're to board the train
in Munich and retrieve the book.

40:28.533 --> 40:30.299
I will be waiting
at Nuremberg Station

40:30.301 --> 40:31.804
for your arrival.

40:33.238 --> 40:35.006
And as for the toymaker.

40:37.307 --> 40:38.776
<i>My preference...</i>

40:39.510 --> 40:41.112
<i>is that you kill him...</i>

40:42.580 --> 40:44.182
<i>slowly.</i>

40:45.649 --> 40:47.283
LANDON: I know
the story I've told you

40:47.285 --> 40:48.720
is somewhat farfetched...

40:49.187 --> 40:53.158
but I have it on good authority
that the book holds great power.

40:53.825 --> 40:56.158
You don't have to believe
everything I've told you,

40:56.160 --> 40:58.194
you just need to know
how imperative it is

40:58.196 --> 41:01.900
that we retrieve the book
and protect the toymaker.

41:02.700 --> 41:05.167
This is an artists
interpretation

41:05.169 --> 41:06.437
of Amos Blackwood

41:06.805 --> 41:09.875
based on witness accounts
in the town of Rosenheim.

41:10.743 --> 41:12.578
You will board the train
in Munich.

41:12.810 --> 41:14.910
It's important
that you locate Mr. Blackwood

41:14.912 --> 41:17.479
and the book before the train
reaches Nuremberg.

41:17.481 --> 41:20.852
We believe the Nazis will be
waiting there for his arrival.

41:22.086 --> 41:26.156
You are one of the agency's
most valuable secret agents.

41:27.057 --> 41:30.928
I know we can count on you
to succeed in this mission.

41:36.368 --> 41:37.369
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

41:58.390 --> 42:00.158
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

42:00.859 --> 42:04.930
[SPEAKING GERMAN]

42:15.472 --> 42:17.108
Evening, officer.

42:28.919 --> 42:30.388
Your ticket, sir.

42:33.725 --> 42:34.960
Uh... uh... uh.

42:36.493 --> 42:37.495
[THUDS]

42:39.631 --> 42:43.102
[TRAIN WHISTLE BLOWING]

43:12.664 --> 43:14.198
AMOS: The coast is clear.

43:19.671 --> 43:21.006
Don't worry.

43:21.805 --> 43:24.041
We will be out
of the country soon.

43:25.711 --> 43:27.011
Then finally...

43:28.147 --> 43:29.481
we will be free.

43:43.761 --> 43:45.296
[ENGINE REVVING]

44:16.227 --> 44:18.062
You don't remember me, do you?

44:21.298 --> 44:22.600
You.

44:26.738 --> 44:27.940
AMOS: <i>I do.</i>

44:30.374 --> 44:31.409
Esther?

44:37.682 --> 44:39.051
So sorry.

44:39.584 --> 44:40.850
I'm so sorry.

44:40.852 --> 44:43.388
I shouldn't have buried you,
I... I--

44:43.854 --> 44:45.122
You had to.

44:45.957 --> 44:47.589
The Nazis would
have found the book

44:47.591 --> 44:49.193
and killed you if you hadn't.

44:50.495 --> 44:51.530
I understand.

44:52.597 --> 44:54.299
But why are you here?

44:55.566 --> 44:57.368
I know you want to escape,

44:57.803 --> 44:59.872
but you can never escape
the memories.

45:06.443 --> 45:07.744
I know.

45:07.979 --> 45:09.681
But if you don't deal with it...

45:10.281 --> 45:12.549
no matter where you go,
no matter what you do,

45:12.551 --> 45:15.520
the ghosts of the past
will always be with you.

45:25.930 --> 45:27.231
Excuse me.

45:27.999 --> 45:30.435
- Have you seen this man?
- <i>Nein.</i>

45:44.316 --> 45:45.450
Excuse me.

45:45.816 --> 45:47.452
Have you seen this man?

45:48.153 --> 45:49.187
<i>Nein.</i>

46:02.533 --> 46:04.135
Excuse me.

46:04.468 --> 46:06.137
Have you seen this man?

46:07.338 --> 46:08.406
<i>Nein.</i>

46:13.144 --> 46:14.511
You.

46:14.812 --> 46:16.281
Have you seen this man?

46:25.957 --> 46:27.825
AMOS: Fear not, my children.

46:28.392 --> 46:31.530
We will be in Nuremberg
soon enough.

46:32.229 --> 46:34.565
Why do you call the dolls
your children?

46:36.667 --> 46:38.035
It's you again.

46:40.437 --> 46:43.709
You cannot escape your demons
just by leaving home.

46:44.876 --> 46:46.575
If you truly want to heal
your soul

46:46.577 --> 46:48.280
you have to look within.

46:49.379 --> 46:51.515
Why can't you
just leave me alone?

46:51.883 --> 46:53.184
Leave me alone!

46:53.718 --> 46:56.321
It's your imagination
that brought me here.

46:57.155 --> 46:59.221
All you have to do
is stop thinking about me

46:59.223 --> 47:00.624
and I'll disappear.

47:06.064 --> 47:09.234
What is it about my death
that haunts you so much?

47:10.135 --> 47:12.470
- I don't know.
- Yes, you do.

47:13.504 --> 47:14.639
Tell me.

47:19.910 --> 47:21.479
Unburden yourself.

47:22.981 --> 47:24.249
It's time.

47:34.225 --> 47:38.528
AMOS: <i>When I married Mary,
it was the happiest moment</i>

47:38.530 --> 47:40.165
<i>of my life.</i>

47:41.031 --> 47:44.669
<i>I felt I had finally found
my soulmate.</i>

47:45.669 --> 47:49.604
<i>Then our children, Hans
and Agnes, came along.</i>

47:49.606 --> 47:52.743
<i>I considered them
to be gifts from God.</i>

47:53.178 --> 47:55.747
<i>My family meant the world to me.</i>

47:56.914 --> 47:59.216
<i>I truly loved them.</i>

48:01.151 --> 48:05.356
<i>But I also loved my work.</i>

48:07.124 --> 48:11.261
<i>I know Mary felt I put
my work before her.</i>

48:11.629 --> 48:13.030
<i>I didn't mean to,</i>

48:13.363 --> 48:16.667
<i>there just weren't enough hours
in the day.</i>

48:17.301 --> 48:22.274
<i>Eventually, Mary found
the attention she deserved</i>

48:22.973 --> 48:24.642
<i>from someone else.</i>

48:27.178 --> 48:30.482
MARY: You know,
I'm going to leave Amos.

48:31.948 --> 48:33.684
- MAN: Really?
- MARY: Yes.

48:34.285 --> 48:36.221
I can't go on living a lie.

48:38.089 --> 48:39.758
MAN: He owns the cottage.

48:40.357 --> 48:42.126
Where are you going to go?

48:43.394 --> 48:45.660
I thought the children
and I could come

48:45.662 --> 48:47.331
and stay with you.

48:49.633 --> 48:51.635
Why don't you want
us to be together?

48:56.006 --> 48:57.809
We are having a lot of fun...

48:58.843 --> 48:59.844
but,

49:00.243 --> 49:02.713
my family expects me
to marry soon.

49:03.314 --> 49:05.247
It wouldn't fit
their expectations

49:05.249 --> 49:07.585
to take on
another man's children.

49:10.220 --> 49:12.556
AMOS: <i>He broke her heart.</i>

49:13.591 --> 49:18.864
<i>Just like she broke mine
by taking solace in his arms.</i>

49:20.564 --> 49:21.732
<i>But then...</i>

49:23.801 --> 49:26.504
<i>she did the unthinkable.</i>

50:32.303 --> 50:33.771
[BIRDS CHIRPING]

50:41.613 --> 50:42.714
[SCREAMS]

50:55.026 --> 50:59.297
[AMOS YELLING] No!

51:00.064 --> 51:02.466
God, no!

51:08.106 --> 51:11.575
[AMOS CRYING]

51:28.693 --> 51:31.629
That is why your death
haunts me.

51:36.334 --> 51:38.536
That night you died
in my arms...

51:39.537 --> 51:43.607
it reminded me of cradling
my Agnes in the... [INAUDIBLE]

51:47.510 --> 51:50.614
I've tried all I can to suppress
the pain of that loss...

51:53.917 --> 51:55.053
but I can't.

51:56.687 --> 51:57.988
I just can't.

52:00.457 --> 52:04.495
What happened to your children,
it's not your fault.

52:06.030 --> 52:07.966
Why do the ones we love...

52:08.732 --> 52:09.868
the most...

52:12.202 --> 52:13.604
just disappear?

52:14.772 --> 52:15.906
Hm?

52:16.406 --> 52:18.676
While the... the rest of us...

52:19.609 --> 52:21.646
we're just left here to suffer.

52:23.680 --> 52:24.481
But maybe...

52:25.048 --> 52:28.683
God, the universe,
whatever you want to call it,

52:28.685 --> 52:31.356
has bigger plans for your life.

52:32.756 --> 52:35.089
It may not be
what you had planned,

52:35.091 --> 52:37.561
but maybe this is your destiny.

52:38.129 --> 52:39.727
Some people
have to go through hell

52:39.729 --> 52:41.832
before they find their paradise.

52:51.676 --> 52:52.777
Excuse me?

52:53.477 --> 52:55.646
Have you seen this man
on the train?

53:26.711 --> 53:28.146
[GRUNTS]

54:17.861 --> 54:20.697
It's the conductor.
I need to see your ticket.

54:29.039 --> 54:30.607
Can I see your ticket, sir?

54:30.975 --> 54:32.210
Yes, of course.

54:39.182 --> 54:40.551
Have a safe journey.

54:41.017 --> 54:42.019
Thank you.

55:38.075 --> 55:39.511
[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

55:42.546 --> 55:47.584
- Hey, do you work here?
- Yes. It's my first shift.

55:48.885 --> 55:52.222
There was only two conductors
on the train from Versachem.

55:52.823 --> 55:54.558
Neither one of them was you.

55:55.191 --> 55:58.361
One of the conductors
had a family emergency.

55:58.863 --> 56:02.232
He got off in Munich.
I took over for him.

56:13.577 --> 56:15.312
[BONES CRACKING]

56:21.419 --> 56:22.787
OFFICER: Excuse me.

56:23.254 --> 56:25.089
Perhaps, you can help me.

56:26.289 --> 56:27.791
What with, officer?

56:28.691 --> 56:30.294
I'm looking for someone.

56:31.796 --> 56:33.931
I'm looking for this man.

56:34.564 --> 56:36.200
Have you seen him on the train?

56:38.336 --> 56:40.671
Yeah. He's on this train.

56:41.338 --> 56:42.472
Where is he?

56:43.372 --> 56:47.044
He has a private compartment
a couple of carriages down.

56:48.144 --> 56:50.047
Very good. Danke.

56:58.156 --> 57:01.325
- [DOOR KNOCKING]
- AMOS: <i>Yes, who is it?</i>

57:01.591 --> 57:02.992
Train maintenance.

57:03.327 --> 57:04.727
We have a fault.

57:04.729 --> 57:06.694
We need to check
your compartment.

57:06.696 --> 57:08.198
It won't take long.

57:26.550 --> 57:27.785
Get inside.

57:30.153 --> 57:32.623
- Do you have the book?
- AMOS: Yes, I have the book.

57:34.225 --> 57:36.493
Then, stay with me
if you want to survive.

57:36.894 --> 57:40.231
- No, my kids. I have to...
- There isn't time, come on!

57:41.298 --> 57:42.300
Let's go.

57:58.649 --> 58:00.184
Get out of the way.

58:08.357 --> 58:10.827
Hey, you're not allowed
to have firearms on this train.

58:11.060 --> 58:13.363
- [GUNSHOT FIRES]
- [WOMAN SCREAMING]

58:41.792 --> 58:44.162
Give me that fucking gun.

58:46.097 --> 58:48.062
There is a lot of things
I might do

58:48.064 --> 58:50.200
with a gun pressed to my head.

58:51.033 --> 58:54.003
Giving up my weapon
is not one of them.

58:54.437 --> 58:58.008
- I'm going to count to three.
- Count to five if you like.

58:58.575 --> 59:01.144
I'm still not surrendering
my firearm!

59:01.745 --> 59:04.314
Then it's goodnight, my friend.

59:13.691 --> 59:15.093
[BOTH GRUNTING]

59:30.374 --> 59:32.410
[GUNSHOT FIRES]

59:55.332 --> 59:56.367
FUCHS: It's okay.

59:56.834 --> 59:58.169
It's over now.

59:58.602 --> 59:59.904
It's okay.

01:00:00.303 --> 01:00:01.506
It's okay.

01:00:07.843 --> 01:00:09.479
My name is Fuchs.

01:00:10.147 --> 01:00:12.817
I work for the people
who are on your side.

01:00:13.651 --> 01:00:15.353
I want to keep you safe.

01:00:16.486 --> 01:00:20.423
They consider you to be
as important as the book.

01:00:21.258 --> 01:00:24.095
Then, it's okay if I keep a hold
of it, yes?

01:00:24.627 --> 01:00:26.164
If that's what you want.

01:00:29.966 --> 01:00:32.970
- [FUCHS LAUGHS]
- AMOS: What's so funny?

01:00:33.736 --> 01:00:34.905
You know,

01:00:35.405 --> 01:00:39.209
I didn't expect
you to just hand over the book.

01:00:40.443 --> 01:00:41.511
Pardon?

01:00:42.680 --> 01:00:43.981
The book.

01:00:44.981 --> 01:00:47.952
I didn't expect you
to just give it to me.

01:00:48.885 --> 01:00:51.254
What the hell did you expect?

01:00:53.624 --> 01:00:54.859
Pry it,

01:00:55.292 --> 01:00:56.894
from your cold,

01:00:57.260 --> 01:01:00.030
dead fingers.

01:01:02.865 --> 01:01:04.968
I thought you were on my side.

01:01:05.702 --> 01:01:07.138
